Hey @Fish | lium.io  Some of these opinions are personal and may not reflect SN2 as a whole. I'm actually not against WC, but I am against it in it's current form. I believe there are benefits to WC, especially in encouraging validator diversity now, and in the future with dTAO. Proof-of-Weights and its success isn't dependent solely on SN2 but requires participation from a majority of the network.  It's open-source so no lock-in with SN2.

Proof-of-Weights is not a solution to Weight Copying. Its sole purpose is to ensure, with cryptographic certainty, which validators are performing the prescribed computation and which are not. For PoW to be effective, we are currently drafting a Bittensor Improvement Proposal to enable a chain-level hyperparameter. This will allow subnets to individually set a curve for WC based on validator size (staked amount) and adjust vtrust accordingly. This approach would allow new validators to enter, WC, and grow, while disincentivizing larger validators from WC unless the SN operator finds it beneficial for bandwidth efficiency.

Hello, thanks for the in depth questions! Indeed, `check_miner_axon` is out of date, but it is planned to be upgraded in the near future. In terms of use cases for these endpoints, `QueryZkProof` is intended to be used for a generic request to any circuit supported by miners, with validators specifying a model ID and arbitrary input data to be processed. The format of query input can change depending on the model specified and proof system used by that model. `QueryForProofAggregation` is currently unused for any models, but in the future this will allow the network to produce and combine collaborative proofs for very large circuits. Essentially a circuit that is broken into fractional pieces and compiled into one single, succinct proof by the miner.
`ProofOfWeightsSynapse` is used for current proof of weights model queries - and is intended to be used alongside our Proof of Weights SDK to allow validators across any subnet to request a proof representing a change they made to weights for any miner on their subnet. 

For example, a validator on any subnet can supply the miner's input along with validator provided metrics to Omron. Miners here will then do the work to compute the updated weight for the miner(s) requested, and supply cryptographic proof back to validators on SN2. Validators on SN2 verify that the proof is valid for the subnet requested and inputs supplied by the external validator. Afterwords, validators on SN2 provide this proof back to the requesting validator (who is validating on another subnet) along with the updated weight(s). External validators now have cryptographic proof that they acted honestly to update weight(s) for miners correctly based on each subnet's incentive mechanism.

- Circuits for proof of weights should be rolled out to each subnet within the chain to prepare each subnet for the chain level integration and drive adoption of the feature.
- A BIT proposal is being worked on for the initial implementation of proof of weights into the chain. This first BIT proposal adds hyperparameters allowing subnet owners to enable proof verification on their subnets whenever validators supply updated weights to the chain, compelling all validators to run the incentive mechanism per the subnet owner's definition.
- The second BIT proposal required is to integrate Proof of Weights with commit reveal. This will improve both commit reveal and proof of weights. By hiding the inputs to the incentive circuits, weights can be revealed to the chain immediately, allowing instant feedback to miners while preserving the functionality of commit reveal. When inputs are then revealed, a peer prediction style method is proposed to detect instances of consensus copying through input prediction or reverse engineering of the circuits themselves. Through the use of peer prediction we aim to detect input outliers (consensus copiers) and reduce the profitability of weight copying to a point where it is more economical to leverage child hotkey.

In regards to bandwidth, Omron's current capacity is already enough compute power to handle Proof of Weights in the worst case. Assuming all 64 subnets had weight setting as the most often (every 100 blocks or max 72 times per sn per day). With 64 subnets and ~30 validators this equates to ~140k/day. Omron conservatively runs over 300,000 proofs per day on average. We are confident this scales with competition and the magic of the Bittensor incentive mechanisms.
